{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Failure boundary is model extraction quality on real legal text, not local wiring. A stubbed extractor can always return expected keys and hide misses on ambiguous phrasing, so mocking would miss real failures (LLM-DEP=yes). No real OS/network requirement is stated, and this is a single reviewer behavior (not multi-step pipeline), so System/Workflow are not required.","test_description":"Run the real clause-extractor model on a curated set of real contracts with adjudicated key-term ground truth; assert recall for parties/dates/obligations/penalties meets threshold and log missed terms for error analysis.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires real model outputs; lower-level deterministic tests cannot catch semantic extraction misses.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The risk assessor flags language that would be problematic under the configured risk policy, even when the problematic phrasing is indirect or euphemistic.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on nuanced semantic judgment ('indirect or euphemistic'), which is model-output quality and can vary across runs/prompts (LLM-DEP=yes). Integration tests with fixed stubs would likely always pass and hide real miss-classifications. Not Workflow because this is one reviewer only.","test_description":"Evaluate the real risk-assessor model on a labeled corpus containing direct and indirect/euphemistic risky clauses under a fixed policy config; assert precision/recall at agreed thresholds and verify hard euphemism cases are flagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Only real model inference can expose failures on euphemistic language.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.88,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on substantive legal-compliance interpretation by the AI reviewer for jurisdiction-specific requirements (LLM-DEP=yes). The behavior text does not require real external API/OS effects, so System is not the minimum. It is a single checker behavior, so Workflow is disqualified by the behavior scope.","test_description":"Run the real compliance-checker model on jurisdiction-tagged contracts with expert-labeled compliance outcomes and requirement-level rationales; assert agreement metrics and requirement coverage for each jurisdiction configuration.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The described test directly exercises model judgment quality; deterministic stubs would not catch this class of failure.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments (e.g., extractor says 'standard' but risk assessor says 'high risk'), the merge step preserves both assessments with attribution.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at a local module boundary: merge logic must correctly combine two reviewer outputs and keep attribution. This can be caught by wiring real local reviewer-output schemas into the merge component; no real OS/network/subprocess is needed (REAL-INFRA=no). Correctness here is merge contract preservation, not real AI quality (LLM-DEP=no for this behavior), so Agentic/Workflow are disqualified by behavior text focused on 'merge step preserves both assessments with attribution'.","test_description":"Feed merge with realistic extractor and risk-assessor output objects (including same-clause conflicting labels) through the actual serialization/deserialization path used in production; assert unified report contains both assessments, clause identity is stable, and reviewer attribution fields are preserved.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test exercises cross-module data handoff and schema alignment, which is beyond pure unit logic but below system/agentic.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting results, merging into a unified report — completes correctly for a real contract without losing any individual reviewer's findings.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This explicitly requires a full agent pipeline with multiple AI reviewers plus merge. Real failure can emerge from multi-step orchestration (parallel dispatch, collection, consolidation) combined with non-deterministic reviewer outputs; single-step Agentic tests cannot catch cross-step loss/regression. System alone is insufficient because the critical boundary includes multiple agentic stages (MULTI-STEP=yes).","test_description":"Execute end-to-end pipeline on real contracts using all three real reviewers in parallel under production-like orchestration; verify final report contains each reviewer’s findings (no dropped clauses/flags/compliance items), includes conflict handling output, and remains complete across repeated runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires multi-agent orchestration with real model steps; lower levels miss pipeline-level loss bugs.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.75}}]}
